      <hedline>
        <hl1>Park Avenue Vista</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Constantine G Vasiliadis letter responds to June 12 Metro Matters column on demolition of New York Coliseum, which has opened up east-west vista at Columbus Circle; suggests former Pan Am Building, now Met Life Building, be demolished to open up north-south vista on Park Ave</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Now that an east-west vista has opened at Columbus Circle with the demolition of the Coliseum (Metro Matters column, June 12), thought should be given to opening up a north-south vista on Park Avenue with demolition of another monolith: the former Pan Am Building, now the Met Life Building.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Now that an east-west vista has opened at Columbus Circle with the demolition of the Coliseum (Metro Matters column, June 12), thought should be given to opening up a north-south vista on Park Avenue with demolition of another monolith: the former Pan Am Building, now the Met Life Building.</p>
        <p>These structures from the 1950's and 60's, together with the loss of Penn Station, will remain forever the catastrophic architectural legacy of that era.</p>
        <p>CONSTANTINE G. VASILIADIS  Mahwah, N.J., June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
